{
  "text": "It is equally important to highlight the progress that has already been made on modeling sophisticated background knowledge in partition-based schemes. One line has focused on taking into account other, known releases, such as previous publications by the same organization (called \"sequential\" or \"incremental\" releases, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] ) and multiple views of the same data set [CITATION_6] . In this paper, we deal with the case when the publisher is not aware of other anonymized releases. Another line has considered incorporating knowledge of the partitioning algorithm used to group individuals [CITATION_7] . Most relevant to this paper are works that have sought to model unknown background knowledge. Martin et al. [CITATION_8] and Chen et al. [CITATION_9] provide complexity measures for an adversary's side information (roughly, they measure the size of the smallest formula within a CNF-like class that can encode the side information). Both works design schemes that provably resist attacks based on side information whose complexity is below a given threshold.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "304685",
    "[CITATION_2]": "264041",
    "[CITATION_3]": "11996464",
